{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9d5f7629-bb61-4efc-92f6-95fc8bf06e2e","content":"## What Changed\n\nC# 14 introduces **implicit span conversions** — `T[]` now implicitly converts to `ReadOnlySpan<T>`. This changes overload resolution for `.Contains()`:\n\n| Version | `array.Contains(num)` resolves to |\n|---------|-----------------------------------|\n| C# 13 / .NET 9 | `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)` ✅ |\n| C# 14 / .NET 10 | `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` ❌ |\n\nThe span-based overload wins because `ReadOnlySpan<int>` is a more specific match for `int[]` than `IEnumerable<int>`. Expression trees **cannot represent `ref struct` types** like `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, so the expression tree fails.\n\n## How to Fix\n\n**Option 1** — Cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` to force the old resolution:\n\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n```\n\n**Option 2** — Call `Enumerable.Contains` explicitly (no extension-method syntax):\n\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n```\n\nBoth approaches bypass the new implicit span conversion and bind to the expression-tree-compatible `Enumerable.Contains` overload. If you're building expression trees **programmatically** (via `Expression.Call` / reflection), make sure you resolve the `MethodInfo` from `System.Linq.Enumerable`, not `System.MemoryExtensions`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"727e0e52-c325-46f7-afc2-74c7877e6a09","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 that affects LINQ expression trees calling `.Contains()` on `int[]` arrays, specifically when compiled with `preferInterpretation: true`.\n\nLet me think about what changed in .NET 10 / C# 14 that would cause this.\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, there's a significant change related to extension methods. C# 14 introduces **extension members** (the new `extension` keyword), and more relevantly, the overload resolution for extension methods may have changed.\n\nBut more specifically, I think this is about the `System.Linq.Enumerable.Contains<T>()` method vs `System.MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>()`.\n\n\nThe compiler in .NET 10 / C# 14 now prefers `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>()` over `Enumerable.Contains<T>()` when working with arrays, since arrays implicitly convert to `Span<T>` or `ReadOnlySpan<T>`. The problem is that these span types are ref structs, which can't be used in expression trees, so the compilation fails when the expression tree tries to capture this method call.\n\nActually, wait—the user mentioned it throws at runtime, not compile time, which suggests the expression tree is being built successfully but failing during interpretation. Let me reconsider: in .NET 9, `array.Contains(num)` resolved to the `Enumerable.Contains` overload, which works fine in expression trees, but now it's resolving to the span-based overload instead. ves `array.Contains(num)` to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<int>, int)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains(IEnumerable<int>, int)`. Since expression trees can't contain calls with `ref struct` types like `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, this should fail at compile time, but the user is seeing a runtime error instead—which suggests either the expression tree is being constructed differently or the compile-time check was somehow bypassed. When the expression tree interpreter tries to invoke this method, it fails because it can't handle the implicit conversion from `int[]` to `ReadOnlySpan<int>` at runtime—that conversion isn't something the expression tree interpreter can execute. I'm thinking through the fixes: either explicitly calling `Enumerable.Contains()` to avoid the span-based overload, or casting the array to `IEnumerable<int>` first to force the right method resolution.\n\nActually, I need to dig into the C# 14 and .NET 10 breaking changes more carefully. The core issue is that C# 14 introduced implicit conversions from `T[]` to `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, which changes how overload resolution works. Before C# 14, calling `Contains` on an array would resolve to the `Enumerable.Contains()` method that takes `IEnumerable<int>`. But now with the new implicit span conversion, the overload resolution prefers `MemoryExtensions.Contains()` which takes `ReadOnlySpan<int>`—and that's a conversion the expression tree interpreter can't handle.\n\nThe tricky part is that expression trees don't support `ref struct` types like `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, so when the compiler tries to compile this into an expression tree, it should fail at compile time. But the user is reporting a runtime error, which suggests either they're building the expression tree programmatically, or there's something else going on with how the compiler is handling this scenario. The compiler should throw a compile-time error about expression trees not supporting ref struct types like `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, but the user says it's a runtime error. Maybe the expression tree is being constructed programmatically through reflection rather than via a lambda, which would let it compile but fail when the expression is evaluated. Or perhaps this is specific to certain preview versions of .NET where the behavior differs. Thinking through whether this could be an expression tree interpreter issue in .NET 10, or if the real culprit is C# 14's implicit span conversion changing how `array.Contains(num)` resolves—which would break expression trees since they can't handle span parameters. The most likely fix is explicitly calling `Enumerable.Contains` or casting to `IEnumerable<int>`. The expression tree can't represent `ref struct` types like `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, so the compiler falls back to `Enumerable.Contains` in expression tree contexts to avoid breaking changes. The practical fix is to explicitly cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` or call `Enumerable.Contains` directly to ensure the right overload is selected. Enumerable<T>` for arrays.\n\nIn expression tree lambdas, the C# 14 spec says implicit span conversions don't apply, so `array.Contains(num)` should still resolve to `Enumerable.Contains` even with the new feature. But if the user is building expression trees programmatically through reflection, the runtime might be picking a different overload in .NET 10, or the behavior could have shifted.\n\nLet me look more carefully at what the user's code is actually doing... thing is the user probably has a lambda expression tree that's somehow triggering a runtime error, which suggests either they're building it programmatically or there's a version-specific compiler behavior I'm not fully accounting for. The most practical approach is to explain the span conversion issue and offer a workaround.\n\nI'll focus on the two main fixes: casting to `IEnumerable<int>` to avoid the span overload, or explicitly calling `Enumerable.Contains` instead. This should resolve the issue regardless of whether it's manifesting at compile time or runtime.","outputTokens":4313,"requestId":"6C24:1619CB:CAEDD7:EB1C77:69FE8588"},"id":"dd64ec56-12fc-4512-ac9c-f398952efe8c","timestamp":"2026-05-09T00:54:51.272Z","parentId":"df6287fa-4984-4426-a53f-7d7d607a8740"}
